Exercise 1 (R output required)

1

Let’s check the linear regression assumptions that we can test prior to running the linear model. First, check and tell us whether the x and y variables are linearly related. Next, please check and tell us whether the y variable is normally distributed. As a reminder, having a normally distributed y variable is not a specific assumption for a linear regression, but we can use it as a proxy to understand whether our errors will likely be normally distributed (which is an assumption of the linear regression!).

  1. y variable: CONT x variable: INTG+DMNR According to plots, x and y variables are not linearly related.
plot(CONT~INTG+DMNR,data=USJudgeRatings)

(2)normality

shapiro.test(USJudgeRatings$CONT)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  USJudgeRatings$CONT
## W = 0.93274, p-value = 0.01445

p value is below 0.05. So null hypothsis that CONT are normally distributed is rejected. So y variables are not normally distributed.

2

Now run the linear regression and check the remaining assumptions. Are the errors homoscedastic and normally distributed? To test for homoscedasticity, you can use the Breusch-Pagan test in the lmtest package. To check for normality, you should use the shapiro wilk test and plot a qqplot.

lmmod1 = lm(CONT~INTG+DMNR,data=USJudgeRatings)
summary(lmmod1)

homoscedastic

bptest(lmmod1)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  lmmod1
## BP = 0.18159, df = 2, p-value = 0.9132
ncvTest(lmmod1)
## Non-constant Variance Score Test 
## Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
## Chisquare = 0.378373, Df = 1, p = 0.53848

In Breusch-Pagan test, p-value = 0.9132. P -value is greater than 0.05. In the Non-constant Variance Score Test, p=0.53848. Both of these results show that our p-value is > 0.05, therefore we fail to reject the null hypothesis of homoscedasticity, and our residuals are homoscedastic.

normality of errors

qqPlot(residuals(lmmod1),id=FALSE)

shapiro.test(residuals(lmmod1))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  residuals(lmmod1)
## W = 0.92583, p-value = 0.00839

Most part of residuals fall within the dotted blue lines, and p-value is larger than 0.05. So the null hypothsis that errors are normally distributed is not rejected. Errors are normally distributed.
